        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
        The Nintendo way of business
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         In 1889, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-24-05-2025-fusajiro-yamauchi" target="_blank">Fusajiro Yamauchi</a> wasn’t trying to invent the future of gaming. He established Yamauchi Nintendo and manufactured Hanafuda, a traditional Japanese flower card. By 1902, he began producing Western-style playing cards, initially for export but eventually gaining traction at home. A few decades later, in 1951, the company began to mass-produce plastic cards, and Disney character prints made it a hit. But the real game hadn’t started yet.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/donkey-kong-arcade-game-screenshot-mario-pauline.jpg" alt="Donkey Kong is a legendary arcade game that introduced players to Mario and set the stage for one of gaming’s most iconic rivalries" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
            Donkey Kong is a legendary arcade game that introduced players to Mario and set the stage for one of gaming’s most iconic rivalries. Credits: theboxhub.com</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            In the early 1960s, Nintendo realized that playing cards, fun as they were, had minimal staying power. They tried everything from rice and love hotels to mechanical toys. Eventually, they hit a jackpot with something called the Beam Gun, Japan’s first electronic toy. It was a fun gadget and Nintendo’s first real step into the world of interactive entertainment.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         By the 1970s, the company had begun tinkering with video games, a platform still trying to find its legs. Its early arcade titles like Sheriff, Space Fever, and Radar Scope had mixed impact, with the latter nearly sinking the company. Instead of folding, Nintendo reworked Radar Scope and handed it to a young designer named Shigeru Miyamoto. In 1981, <i><a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-24-05-2025-donkey-kong" target="_blank">Donkey Kong</a></i> was released and became Nintendo’s first big hit.
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
