          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Level up or die trying</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          By the 1980s, the markets were flooded with poor-quality games, frustrating consumers. But Nintendo saw a prospect in the wreckage. In 1983, it launched the <i>Family Computer</i> or <i>Famicom</i> in Japan. It came loaded with custom CPUs and graphics processors, offering smoother experience than most competitors. Later, it would debut in the West as the <i><a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-24-05-2025-nintendo-entertainment-system" target="_blank">Nintendo Entertainment System</a></i> (NES).
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Nintendo's growth during this dark chapter was due to a two-pronged strategy. First, they released great games like Super Mario Bros., which became iconic. Second, they changed the narrative. Instead of selling the NES as “just another console” like the flailing Atari 2600 or Mattel’s Intellivision, Nintendo positioned its product as an entertainment system. This was a technical and psychological pivot. 
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          They removed the NES from the electronics aisle and placed it in the toy section, right alongside the Barbies and Hot Wheels. With titles like <i>Excitebike, Metroid, Punch-Out!!</i>, and <i>The Legend of Zelda</i>, Nintendo sold games and told stories. They invited players into rich, immersive worlds, and suddenly, gaming was imaginative.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Nintendo’s switch</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         In 1989, Nintendo dropped <i>Game Boy</i> and sparked an era of handheld gaming. It was compact, addictive, and wildly successful. A year later, they followed it up with the <i><a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-24-05-2025-super-nintendo-entertainment-system" target="_blank">Super Nintendo Entertainment System</a></i> (SNES), continuing their home console dominance. In 1995, Nintendo took a bold leap with the Virtual Boy, their first foray into what they hoped would be virtual reality, but failed.</p>
         </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/nintendo-switch-lite-vs-switch-vs-oled-comparison.jpg" alt="The Nintendo Switch lineup provides versatile gaming with the portable Switch Lite, the hybrid standard Switch, and the premium OLED model for enhanced visuals" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
The Nintendo Switch lineup provides versatile gaming with the portable Switch Lite, the hybrid standard Switch, and the premium OLED model for enhanced visuals. Credits: Scott Stein/CNET 
</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          The Nintendo 64 was released in 1996. While it had its flaws, it also delivered legendary titles and introduced 3D gaming to the masses. Then came 2004. Nintendo released the <i>Nintendo DS</i>, a handheld console with dual screens and a touchscreen feature. It was risky, it was brilliant, and it became one of the company’s best-selling devices. In 2006, they unveiled the <i>Wii</i>, a motion-controlled console, and once again, it was a smash hit. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Nintendo tried to merge the spirit of the <i>Wii</i> and DS into a single handheld model, the Wii U. It was confusing to consumers, not well received, and turned out to be the company’s biggest commercial failure since the <i>Virtual Boy</i>. In 2017, Nintendo released the <i><a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-24-05-2025-switch" target="_blank">Switch</a></i>, a hybrid console that could be played at home or on the go. The Switch redefined what modern gaming could look like. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Years later, as we await Switch 2’s release, the Nintendo story remains the same: hype, demand, scarcity, and devotion.</p>
          </mj-text> 
